===Etymology===
From Spanish ''[[maravedí]]'', from Arabic {{ARchar|[[مرابطين]]}} (murābiŧīn) (an inflected plural of {{ARchar|[[مرابط]]}} (murābiŧ)), the name of the Berber rulers of Muslim Spain during the 12th century.  Compare ''[[marabout]]''.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/mærəˈveɪdi/}}

=== Noun ===
{{en-noun}}

# {{historical}} A former [[Spanish]] [[coin]] and unit of currency, originally issued in [[gold]] but later in [[silver]] and [[copper]], discontinued in 1848.
#:*'''1819''': “an thou dost go on to put thy filthy lucre in the balance with thy daughter’s life and honour, by Heaven, I will strip thee of every '''maravedi''' thou hast in the world, before three days are out!” — Walter Scott, ''Ivanhoe''

